&lt;td colspan=&quot;2&quot; class=&quot;diff-lineno&quot;&gt;Line 25:&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;&amp;lt;blockquote&amp;gt;«I admit that human nature is present in many beings without they need to think about it, but I'm adding&amp;#160; this nature is multifaceted » [Gassendi, ''Exercitationes Paradoxicae''; implicitly&amp;#160; atomistic 'soul' envisages equal opportunities but G. doesn't avert his eyes from from what is a 'soul' in down syndrome, severe psychosis, senile dementia etc.. (ed.'s n.)]. &amp;#160;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;&amp;lt;blockquote&amp;gt;«I admit that human nature is present in many beings without they need to think about it, but I'm adding&amp;#160; this nature is multifaceted » [Gassendi, ''Exercitationes Paradoxicae''; implicitly&amp;#160; atomistic 'soul' envisages equal opportunities but G. doesn't avert his eyes from from what is a 'soul' in down syndrome, severe psychosis, senile dementia etc.. (ed.'s n.)]. &amp;#160;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;&amp;quot;Being saved by ills which we may worry, and enjoying leisurely goods at hand in one's circumstance. [...] let's engage to live without regretting past time, and to enjoy the present time as though the next day&amp;#160;  d i d&amp;#160;  n o t&amp;#160; &amp;#160; concern us at all. It comes as a pure pleasure the next day to him who&amp;#160; feels neither greed nor hopes of it; one feels as a nice bonus the moment which one hadn't wrongly hoped for&amp;quot; [''Epicuri Philosophiae Syntagma''. Chap. I]&amp;lt;br&amp;gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;&amp;quot;Being saved by ills which we may worry, and enjoying leisurely goods at hand in one's circumstance. [...] let's engage to live without regretting past time, and to enjoy the present time as though the next day&amp;#160;  d i d&amp;#160;  n o t&amp;#160; &amp;#160; concern us at all. It comes as a pure pleasure the next day to him who&amp;#160; feels neither greed nor hopes of it; one feels as a nice bonus the moment which one hadn't wrongly hoped for&amp;quot; [''Epicuri Philosophiae Syntagma''. Chap. I]&amp;lt;br&amp;gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;−&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;color:black; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #ffe49c; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;His last words before dying: &amp;quot;here's the petty thing that &lt;del class=&quot;diffchange diffchange-inline&quot;&gt;is &lt;/del&gt;life&amp;quot; [Guerard E. (1879)]&amp;lt;/blockquote&amp;gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;+&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;color:black; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #a3d3ff; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;His last words before dying: &amp;quot;here's the petty thing that life &lt;ins class=&quot;diffchange diffchange-inline&quot;&gt;is&lt;/ins&gt;&amp;quot; [Guerard E. (1879)&lt;ins class=&quot;diffchange diffchange-inline&quot;&gt;: unusual words by a person who is going in paradise&lt;/ins&gt;]&amp;lt;/blockquote&amp;gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;Garasse in '' Curious Doctrines of subtle Minds'' (1623) wrote of Italian “sly old foxes difficult to catch as their den has double loophole”. One displayed that the after life's Christian end-goal was a durable pleasure in the ''paradisum voluptatis'' (of pleasure)' as it's called by the Bible; that the Epicureans privileged soul's pleasures and friendship; one wanted to get along with majority and to live separately in spite of everything.&amp;#160; Guy Patin held - not groudlessly - Vanini to be no martyr but a person who “was tired of living and raging of dying” [(1701) ''Naudeana et Patiniana'' p. 31]. These Epicureans wanted to live better, not to get the better. “Mr Naudé has invited me [...] at the (Gassendi' s) house of&amp;#160; Chantilly [...] in order to binge [...] But Naudé drinks just water, Gassendi would feel his body&amp;#160; burning&amp;#160; if he binged [...] it will be a binge, but philosophical [...] in order to get over unsociability (''loup-garou'') ...” [Guy Patin, Letter to Falconet, August 27 1648].&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;Garasse in '' Curious Doctrines of subtle Minds'' (1623) wrote of Italian “sly old foxes difficult to catch as their den has double loophole”. One displayed that the after life's Christian end-goal was a durable pleasure in the ''paradisum voluptatis'' (of pleasure)' as it's called by the Bible; that the Epicureans privileged soul's pleasures and friendship; one wanted to get along with majority and to live separately in spite of everything.&amp;#160; Guy Patin held - not groudlessly - Vanini to be no martyr but a person who “was tired of living and raging of dying” [(1701) ''Naudeana et Patiniana'' p. 31]. These Epicureans wanted to live better, not to get the better. “Mr Naudé has invited me [...] at the (Gassendi' s) house of&amp;#160; Chantilly [...] in order to binge [...] But Naudé drinks just water, Gassendi would feel his body&amp;#160; burning&amp;#160; if he binged [...] it will be a binge, but philosophical [...] in order to get over unsociability (''loup-garou'') ...” [Guy Patin, Letter to Falconet, August 27 1648].&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
