				&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td colspan='4' style='text-align: center;' class='diff-multi'&gt;(One intermediate revision by the same user not shown)&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td colspan=&quot;2&quot; class=&quot;diff-lineno&quot;&gt;Line 1:&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td colspan=&quot;2&quot; class=&quot;diff-lineno&quot;&gt;Line 1:&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;'''''Scientific Method'''''&amp;lt;br&amp;gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;'''''Scientific Method'''''&amp;lt;br&amp;gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;Epicurus' virtue notion is a good attempt of scientific psychology about adaptive conduct by causal/dynamic relationship,&amp;#160; not as a 'reasoning', nor as value system (moralism is out of requirement of universal consistency), nor as theoretic definitions: Prudence is practical, Temperance is relative to good health and wealth [P.D. 8]; Fortitude is gradable (more or less) ; Justice &amp;quot;does not exist in itself (''Kath' eayto'')&amp;quot; [P.D. 33; the last three E. never talked about, and scorned (&amp;#160; “I spit upon the honorable”, U 512)]; they exist as dynamical implement of effects of changeable prudence in human relations (two ways of friendship: gratitude [''Peri dorôn kai charitos''] and security/cordiality [''asphaleian philias'' of P.D. 28; many dedicated books, story rather than precepts]), and in econonomical choices (projection of recollections in the future); an anonymous humble graffito in Pompeii outstandingly epitomizes: «This is a man: reason, past recollections, thankfulness»; as the mind moves the body and is moved by the body, all is matter and has his many-sidedness; they are causal, because agents are gauged by relations of analogy, action, balance (see&amp;#160; below: ''pathologikos tropos kaì o aitiologikos'', ''symmetrêsei'', proportion, somewhere else ''isonomia'' and in Lucr. and Cic.&amp;#160; ''aequilibritas, aequalis distributio'') and temporal/spatial distinctions in sensorial qualities.&amp;lt;br&amp;gt; &amp;#160;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;Epicurus' virtue notion is a good attempt of scientific psychology about adaptive conduct by causal/dynamic relationship,&amp;#160; not as a 'reasoning', nor as value system (moralism is out of requirement of universal consistency), nor as theoretic definitions: Prudence is practical, Temperance is relative to good health and wealth [P.D. 8]; Fortitude is gradable (more or less) ; Justice &amp;quot;does not exist in itself (''Kath' eayto'')&amp;quot; [P.D. 33; the last three E. never talked about, and scorned (&amp;#160; “I spit upon the honorable”, U 512)]; they exist as dynamical implement of effects of changeable prudence in human relations (two ways of friendship: gratitude [''Peri dorôn kai charitos''] and security/cordiality [''asphaleian philias'' of P.D. 28; many dedicated books, story rather than precepts]), and in econonomical choices (projection of recollections in the future); an anonymous humble graffito in Pompeii outstandingly epitomizes: «This is a man: reason, past recollections, thankfulness»; as the mind moves the body and is moved by the body, all is matter and has his many-sidedness; they are causal, because agents are gauged by relations of analogy, action, balance (see&amp;#160; below: ''pathologikos tropos kaì o aitiologikos'', ''symmetrêsei'', proportion, somewhere else ''isonomia'' and in Lucr. and Cic.&amp;#160; ''aequilibritas, aequalis distributio'') and temporal/spatial distinctions in sensorial qualities.&amp;lt;br&amp;gt; &amp;#160;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;−&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;color:black; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #ffe49c; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;Ep. didn't say that swerve/imbalance and voluntary action happen without cause, but only that they depend on one's own causality, that responds to contingencies of credit and blame,&amp;#160; and on our character (that gets us pleasure) and on epilogismòs (that gets advantage for pleasure). Not 'ethical' purpose but “pursues virtue for he pursues advantage” [Demetrius the Laconian' s PHerc 1012]. Aggregative causality cuts off straight [inertial] causality into definite curvilinear change [today we know that differentiation between inorganic and organic causality open a certain degree of freedom through many circular retroactive nets up to intelligent synaptic self-control ]. &amp;quot;concentrated together [atoms], [...] are by nature capable of producing such things and starting such a process&amp;quot; [ ''On Nature'' Book XXV PHerc 697, [34. 4] ARR.; see Talk:Canon]. The very limit of Epicurean soul&amp;#160; freedom (the 'swerve' in ''DRN'', II, 244 is: 'nec plus quam minimum',&amp;#160; translation of ''elachiston'') is recognized by cybernetic homeostasis. For instance body's temperature is more self-regulated than the stone's one, but as far as non-extreme climate, and available caloric foods are there. &amp;quot;If we attempt to force unmodifiable&amp;#160; aspects, we are going to counter our own senses &amp;quot;[Polystratus?, ''Ethical Epicurean Treatise'' Ch. 1, PHerc 346. Capasso ed. 1982]. Limit (''peras'')/impossibility is the main theme of Epicureanism,&amp;#160; too many times accused of dogmatism. He gathered, of course, some fixed points, bar supernatural reasons to be moral for which there is no evidence. But, about impossibility the Epicurean 'more or less' keeps correctly silent. Impossible is not 'gradable' (i.e. analogically approachable, more or less, through the ''kanôn''; see Talk: Canon): 'quite impossible' is a hoary joke; induction is never complete for today epistemology either, so only ''antimartyrêsis''/falsifiability is safe. “(It is not necessary that) because these things do not exist in our experience, they do not exist in other places.” [''On methods of Inference'' PHerc. 1065 item 1. De Lacy' s tr.]&amp;lt;br&amp;gt; &amp;#160;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;+&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;color:black; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #a3d3ff; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;Ep. didn't say that swerve/imbalance and voluntary action happen without cause, but only that they depend on one's own causality, that responds to contingencies of credit and blame,&amp;#160; and on our character (that gets us pleasure) and on epilogismòs (that gets advantage for pleasure&lt;ins class=&quot;diffchange diffchange-inline&quot;&gt;). Traditional virtues observed gods, fathers, law, neighborliness; the basic Epicurean virtue for katastematic pleasure, linked to needs (''chreia''), was prudence (''phronêsis''), that is no suffering (''mete algomen''), only sound fears (''mete tarbomen''), seclusion (''làthe biôsas''), observance of positive laws (''dikaios'');&amp;#160; the wise virtue (''kalos''), linked to betterment, that is natural science (''physiologia''), selected friendship (''philia''),&amp;#160; landownership (''agathos chrematistes''&lt;/ins&gt;). Not 'ethical' purpose but “pursues virtue for he pursues advantage” [Demetrius the Laconian' s PHerc 1012]. Aggregative causality cuts off straight [inertial] causality into definite curvilinear change [today we know that differentiation between inorganic and organic causality open a certain degree of freedom through many circular retroactive nets up to intelligent synaptic self-control ]. &amp;quot;concentrated together [atoms], [...] are by nature capable of producing such things and starting such a process&amp;quot; [ ''On Nature'' Book XXV PHerc 697, [34. 4] ARR.; see Talk:Canon]. The very limit of Epicurean soul&amp;#160; freedom (the 'swerve' in ''DRN'', II, 244 is: 'nec plus quam minimum',&amp;#160; translation of ''elachiston'') is recognized by cybernetic homeostasis. For instance body's temperature is more self-regulated than the stone's one, but as far as non-extreme climate, and available caloric foods are there. &amp;quot;If we attempt to force unmodifiable&amp;#160; aspects, we are going to counter our own senses &amp;quot;[Polystratus?, ''Ethical Epicurean Treatise'' Ch. 1, PHerc 346. Capasso ed. 1982]. Limit (''peras'')/impossibility is the main theme of Epicureanism,&amp;#160; too many times accused of dogmatism. He gathered, of course, some fixed points, bar supernatural reasons to be moral for which there is no evidence. But, about impossibility the Epicurean 'more or less' keeps correctly silent. Impossible is not 'gradable' (i.e. analogically approachable, more or less, through the ''kanôn''; see Talk: Canon): 'quite impossible' is a hoary joke; induction is never complete for today epistemology either, so only ''antimartyrêsis''/falsifiability is safe. “(It is not necessary that) because these things do not exist in our experience, they do not exist in other places.” [''On methods of Inference'' PHerc. 1065 item 1. De Lacy' s tr.]&amp;lt;br&amp;gt; &amp;#160;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;−&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;color:black; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #ffe49c; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;Virtue needs freedom, but a link to nature is inevitable “we must not resist nature but submit to her” [V.S. 21] (belly's central position; death): freedom&amp;#160; acts into intervals with '''''kinetic''''' desires (values). “Therefore were expounded both&amp;#160; states derived from these causes (''aitiôn'') and from drives ('''''kinêseon''''') happening both by instincts/environment and by our motivation (''tên physin kaì tò periechon'')” [''On Nature ''XXV. Arr. 34. 33: ''Ek toutôn tôn aitiôn epistanoysai kai kinêseon tôn te di' êmas kai tôn dià tên physin kaì tò periechon'']. It's a position of no being beyond natural bounds, a passive inward katastematic virtue (easily pleased). In that Epicureans, Stoics, Buddists are on parallel lines in order to avoid vain guilty feelings. Against automatism of terminal illnesses virtue is powerless, but until body is healthy, mental rumination of bodily pleasures and trust of fast recovery out of little pains are common sense; if pleasure doesn't grow and the mean ones are however welcome, being content with steadiness it is common sense too, that is do not suffer without being driven by necessity. But for calculation of positive balance (''epilogismòs'') of mental pleasure' s duration above mental undervaluation (shortness) of pains, wisdom and ''katapyknôsis'' are needed, that is virtues. “So both affections' explanation method and the causes' explanation one” [''On Nature ''XXV. Ibid.: ôste apodedotai kaì o pathologikos tropos kaì o aitiologikos]. Affection explanation teaches us that, in spite pleasure&amp;#160; comes into being from need, and epilogismòs is only roughly rational, joy is real (even among front-line fighters);&amp;#160;  not through long traineeship of Lyceum,&amp;#160; or&amp;#160; training to second life, but through distraction (''distractio'': separation, that is varying habit of the mind through moving pleasures) from evils by pragmatic expertise among partners, and acceptance of present time, the sole extant experience. In that case , worded in rather heterodox terms:&amp;#160; “The chief of all goods, even if there weren’t any other, is that by which he who possesses it advances toward virtue “ [''Vol. Herc. 2'', VII.21 col. XXVIII].&amp;#160; For predisposition and limits, that is body,&amp;#160; to virtue and wisdom, nature has the last word (fighting sleep, death, etc.) and the fools are a crowd: 'the completeness and limit of the flesh', character and bent :''diathesis'' and&amp;#160; ''systasis'',&amp;#160; or ''synethêia'' (habit): “only the Greeks are qualified to practice philosophy”.&amp;#160; Epicureanism reconsiders the nature (body, character, spontaneous groups, intuition) and the phylogenesis. Notwithstanding those, there is a room to move about for freedom which is able to reach virtue. &amp;#160;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;+&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;color:black; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #a3d3ff; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;Virtue needs freedom, but a link to nature is inevitable “we must not resist nature but submit to her” [V.S. 21] (belly's central position; death): freedom&amp;#160; acts into intervals with '''''kinetic''''' desires (values). “Therefore were expounded both&amp;#160; states derived from these causes (''aitiôn'') and from drives ('''''kinêseon''''') happening both by instincts/environment and by our motivation (''tên physin kaì tò periechon'')” [''On Nature ''XXV. Arr. 34. 33: ''Ek toutôn tôn aitiôn epistanoysai kai kinêseon tôn te di' êmas kai tôn dià tên physin kaì tò periechon'']. It's a position of no being beyond natural bounds, a passive inward katastematic virtue (easily pleased). In that Epicureans, Stoics, Buddists are on parallel lines in order to avoid vain guilty feelings. Against automatism of terminal illnesses virtue is powerless, but until body is healthy, mental rumination of bodily pleasures and trust of fast recovery out of little pains are common sense; if pleasure doesn't grow and the mean ones are however welcome, being content with steadiness it is common sense too, that is do not suffer without being driven by necessity. But for calculation of positive balance (''epilogismòs'') of mental pleasure' s duration above mental undervaluation (shortness) of pains, wisdom and ''katapyknôsis'' are needed, that is virtues. “So both affections' explanation method and the causes' explanation one” [''On Nature ''XXV. Ibid.: ôste apodedotai kaì o pathologikos tropos kaì o aitiologikos]. Affection explanation teaches us that, in spite pleasure&amp;#160; comes into being from need, and epilogismòs is only roughly rational, joy is real (even among front-line fighters);&amp;#160;  not through long traineeship of Lyceum,&amp;#160; or&amp;#160; training to second life, but through distraction (''distractio'': separation, that is varying habit of the mind through moving pleasures) from evils by pragmatic expertise among partners, and acceptance of present time, the sole extant experience. In that case , worded in rather heterodox terms:&amp;#160; “The chief of all goods, even if there weren’t any other, is that by which he who possesses it advances toward virtue “ [''Vol. Herc. 2'', VII.21 col. XXVIII].&amp;#160; For predisposition and limits, that is body,&amp;#160; to virtue and wisdom, nature has the last word (fighting sleep, death, etc.) and the fools are a crowd: 'the completeness and limit &lt;ins class=&quot;diffchange diffchange-inline&quot;&gt;(''horos'') &lt;/ins&gt;of the flesh', character and bent :''diathesis'' and&amp;#160; ''systasis'',&amp;#160; or ''synethêia'' (habit): “only the Greeks are qualified to practice philosophy”.&amp;#160; Epicureanism reconsiders the nature (body, character, spontaneous groups, intuition) and the phylogenesis. Notwithstanding those, there is a room to move about for freedom which is able to reach virtue. &amp;#160;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
