&lt;td colspan=&quot;2&quot; class=&quot;diff-lineno&quot;&gt;Line 9:&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;Choices are made by&amp;#160; Epicurean fully responsible anticipation of steady homeostatic (Ep. 'stable') body instincts (inward sensitive), that is natural necessary desires, which yield&amp;#160; ''katastêmatikos'' pleasures (''kata'' means a linear motion of '''falling down''', viz of atomic necessity, for instance of fidgety appetite, of thermoregulation around 37°), whose there are no freedom but only assessment of means (''kat(at)ênagkasmenôs / anagkaiôs'': caused by necessity): &amp;quot;by which alone it is possible to act '''rigidly''' &amp;quot; [''Choices'' XIII]. Real free choices are made by open-ended instincts (of restless Mammalia), Torquatus, in ''De Fin'' 1, 31, calls ''quasi naturalis notio'', almost natural,&amp;#160; with limited freedom, not only genetic but epigenetic and 'nurtured': &amp;quot;congenital ends ''syggenika tele'' [sc. sensations &amp;amp; prolepseis],[...] by which the calculations concerning the things to be chosen or avoided&amp;quot; [Tsouna tr. of ''Choices'' XIII]; there are unsteady ''kinêtikos'' desires, outward sensitive, half automatism half pragmatic statistical reasoning (a complete non-natural reasoning would be useless, vain), which yield “joy and delight” of winning [Diog. L. 136; but his term is Peripatetic; the one used by a genuine Epicurean (Diog Oin.&amp;#160; fr 34,&amp;#160; Smith) is ''praxis'' (''praxeosein''), i.e. action], that yield improvement but is open to calculated risk which are we 'more or less' responsible of; as future days are neither wholly ours, nor wholly not ours; most of all it does be source related to gratification we call neurohormonal response (philosophers considered it 'spiritual', like the wind/''spiritus''; after soul is flied away it lack breath/''spiritus''); the very 'soul' atoms are lighter, round, slippery... and just the same fly away) as they are less palpable than skin and mucosae, but their contribution is higher, coming from recollection and&amp;#160; imagination; freedom of their choice is subordinated to previous necessary desires fulfillment (this case: pleasure or removal of pain, the foundation of behavior), in order to vary possible pleasures and to protract them. “Cyrenaics reject Epicurus’ definition of pleasure&amp;quot;, i.e., the 'removal of pain'” [U451]; on the contrary&amp;#160; as holds Cardanus (see Talk:Pierre Gassendi)&amp;#160; in ''On usefulness derived by troubles'', and Voltaire in ''Precis de l'Ecclésiaste, 30'': “No true pleasures without true needs”, and France in&amp;#160; ''The Epicure's Garden'' “Evil is the sole&amp;#160; ground of good”, today's necessary desires&amp;#160; (removing pain) come first than unnecessary desires&amp;#160; '''''(1)'''''&amp;lt;blockquote&amp;gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;Choices are made by&amp;#160; Epicurean fully responsible anticipation of steady homeostatic (Ep. 'stable') body instincts (inward sensitive), that is natural necessary desires, which yield&amp;#160; ''katastêmatikos'' pleasures (''kata'' means a linear motion of '''falling down''', viz of atomic necessity, for instance of fidgety appetite, of thermoregulation around 37°), whose there are no freedom but only assessment of means (''kat(at)ênagkasmenôs / anagkaiôs'': caused by necessity): &amp;quot;by which alone it is possible to act '''rigidly''' &amp;quot; [''Choices'' XIII]. Real free choices are made by open-ended instincts (of restless Mammalia), Torquatus, in ''De Fin'' 1, 31, calls ''quasi naturalis notio'', almost natural,&amp;#160; with limited freedom, not only genetic but epigenetic and 'nurtured': &amp;quot;congenital ends ''syggenika tele'' [sc. sensations &amp;amp; prolepseis],[...] by which the calculations concerning the things to be chosen or avoided&amp;quot; [Tsouna tr. of ''Choices'' XIII]; there are unsteady ''kinêtikos'' desires, outward sensitive, half automatism half pragmatic statistical reasoning (a complete non-natural reasoning would be useless, vain), which yield “joy and delight” of winning [Diog. L. 136; but his term is Peripatetic; the one used by a genuine Epicurean (Diog Oin.&amp;#160; fr 34,&amp;#160; Smith) is ''praxis'' (''praxeosein''), i.e. action], that yield improvement but is open to calculated risk which are we 'more or less' responsible of; as future days are neither wholly ours, nor wholly not ours; most of all it does be source related to gratification we call neurohormonal response (philosophers considered it 'spiritual', like the wind/''spiritus''; after soul is flied away it lack breath/''spiritus''); the very 'soul' atoms are lighter, round, slippery... and just the same fly away) as they are less palpable than skin and mucosae, but their contribution is higher, coming from recollection and&amp;#160; imagination; freedom of their choice is subordinated to previous necessary desires fulfillment (this case: pleasure or removal of pain, the foundation of behavior), in order to vary possible pleasures and to protract them. “Cyrenaics reject Epicurus’ definition of pleasure&amp;quot;, i.e., the 'removal of pain'” [U451]; on the contrary&amp;#160; as holds Cardanus (see Talk:Pierre Gassendi)&amp;#160; in ''On usefulness derived by troubles'', and Voltaire in ''Precis de l'Ecclésiaste, 30'': “No true pleasures without true needs”, and France in&amp;#160; ''The Epicure's Garden'' “Evil is the sole&amp;#160; ground of good”, today's necessary desires&amp;#160; (removing pain) come first than unnecessary desires&amp;#160; '''''(1)'''''&amp;lt;blockquote&amp;gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;“one '''seeks''' after nothing which does not naturally '''remove pain''' (''mêthen diôkein d mê pephyken algêdona periaipein'') - and such are most of the matters which people take a serious interest in ” [''Choices'' IV]; “things which remove pain arising from need are easy to obtain,” [PD 21]; but next “the mind does not shun pleasure” [P.D. 20; ''tois&amp;#160; oligois arkômetha'', satisfied with a few things (''Men.'' 130)]&amp;lt;/blockquote&amp;gt; to obtain joy and and to choose what is 'at hand' (''eyporistos''), '''''(2)'''''&amp;lt;blockquote&amp;gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;“one '''seeks''' after nothing which does not naturally '''remove pain''' (''mêthen diôkein d mê pephyken algêdona periaipein'') - and such are most of the matters which people take a serious interest in ” [''Choices'' IV]; “things which remove pain arising from need are easy to obtain,” [PD 21]; but next “the mind does not shun pleasure” [P.D. 20; ''tois&amp;#160; oligois arkômetha'', satisfied with a few things (''Men.'' 130)]&amp;lt;/blockquote&amp;gt; to obtain joy and and to choose what is 'at hand' (''eyporistos''), '''''(2)'''''&amp;lt;blockquote&amp;gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;−&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;color:black; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #ffe49c; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;“one does '''not avoid''' what does not prevent [double negation connotes absence of greed] one from having pleasure&amp;#160; -&amp;#160; such as we should consider most matters of improvement to be” [Phld., ''Choices'', IV; Horace's Latin wording ''Quod adest, gratum iuvat'' [S,2,6,13; “What is pleasurable at hand gets improvement”]] aiming at “our feelings of joy” [Phld.''Choices'', VI]; no unnecessary pleasure which is followed by future sure trouble; not avoiding today unnecessary pleasure for never greater future pleasure:&amp;#160; &amp;quot;carpe diem, quam minimum credula postero&amp;quot; [Hor., ''Carm.'' I. 11: &amp;quot;seize the day, trusting as little as possible in the next (day)&amp;quot;; of course one does have to trust in predictable necessities...]; ''mête pheygein d mê kôlyei tên êdonên echein'' ,&amp;#160; ''medèn agan'', ''nihil admirari'' &amp;quot;not to be longing for&amp;quot; [Hor. ''Epist.'' I.6. 1] ; ]; &amp;quot; although you are not master of tomorrow, are postponing today's opportunity (''kairon'')&amp;quot; [V.S. 14]; ''quod sis esse velis nihilque malis'' [Mart.: pursue what you are, and do not prefer any non-existent], as they “may easily be dispelled when they are seen as difficult to fulfill or likely to produce harm” [PD 26];&amp;#160; not “at the cost of excessive troubles” [PD 8; ''fugienda petendis non immiscere'' [Hor., ''Serm''. I, 2, 74]]. The pleasure of overcoming commensurate obstacles - that are up to our aptitudes, like choosing with mastery non-necessary desires (of which most of civilized divisions of labor are part) - is soundly expounded, as a behavior pleasure (not passive, nor sensory, nor muscular, but 'in motion and in action' through the mind); so, even if the mind 'emerges' from motion of the body, &amp;quot;the pleasures of the mind are greater than those of the body&amp;quot; [D.L. 137].&amp;lt;/blockquote&amp;gt;&amp;#160; So a pleasure of virtue (imagination of more rational future or recollection of past advantages) may be chosen&amp;#160; among interchangeable unnecessary desires. Among them the philosophical contemplation of ''prolêpseis'' was stressed (see below). Implementation of choice is to be easy, otherwise is it to be lived as a necessity. As one needs no further necessary thing but pleasure continuity (no predictability), one can and has to vary, that is substitute one pleasure with another, as long as it is innocuous; otherwise they risk becoming border-less, i.e. &lt;del class=&quot;diffchange diffchange-inline&quot;&gt; &lt;/del&gt;whether stressful or vain, ''kene'' ', whether for internal (freedom, habits) or external (causes, competition/consumerism) factors rough confusion:&amp;#160; cithara hardly helps ears aching by contained cerumen [Hor. ''Ep.'' I.2.51]; only what is limited within its ambit is calculable. Only in &lt;del class=&quot;diffchange diffchange-inline&quot;&gt;this &lt;/del&gt;case choice turns into an effective cognitive therapy (shared by intellectualist ethics of Skeptics and Epictetus) as is that of Principal Doctrines.&amp;#160; '''''(3)''''' &amp;lt;blockquote&amp;gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;+&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;color:black; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #a3d3ff; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;“one does '''not avoid''' what does not prevent [double negation connotes absence of greed] one from having pleasure&amp;#160; -&amp;#160; such as we should consider most matters of improvement to be” [Phld., ''Choices'', IV; Horace's Latin wording ''Quod adest, gratum iuvat'' [S,2,6,13; “What is pleasurable at hand gets improvement”]] aiming at “our feelings of joy” [Phld.''Choices'', VI]; no unnecessary pleasure which is followed by future sure trouble; not avoiding today unnecessary pleasure for never greater future pleasure:&amp;#160; &amp;quot;carpe diem, quam minimum credula postero&amp;quot; [Hor., ''Carm.'' I. 11: &amp;quot;seize the day, trusting as little as possible in the next (day)&amp;quot;; of course one does have to trust in predictable necessities...]; ''mête pheygein d mê kôlyei tên êdonên echein'' ,&amp;#160; ''medèn agan'', ''nihil admirari'' &amp;quot;not to be longing for&amp;quot; [Hor. ''Epist.'' I.6. 1] ; ]; &amp;quot; although you are not master of tomorrow, are postponing today's opportunity (''kairon'')&amp;quot; [V.S. 14]; ''quod sis esse velis nihilque malis'' [Mart.: pursue what you are, and do not prefer any non-existent], as they “may easily be dispelled when they are seen as difficult to fulfill or likely to produce harm” [PD 26];&amp;#160; not “at the cost of excessive troubles” [PD 8; ''fugienda petendis non immiscere'' [Hor., ''Serm''. I, 2, 74]]. The pleasure of overcoming commensurate obstacles - that are up to our aptitudes, like choosing with mastery non-necessary desires (of which most of civilized divisions of labor are part) - is soundly expounded, as a behavior pleasure (not passive, nor sensory, nor muscular, but 'in motion and in action' through the mind); so, even if the mind 'emerges' from motion of the body, &amp;quot;the pleasures of the mind are greater than those of the body&amp;quot; [D.L. 137].&amp;lt;/blockquote&amp;gt;&amp;#160; So a pleasure of virtue (imagination of more rational future or recollection of past advantages) may be chosen&amp;#160; among interchangeable unnecessary desires. Among them the philosophical contemplation of ''prolêpseis'' was stressed (see below). Implementation of choice is to be easy, otherwise is it to be lived as a necessity. As one needs no further necessary thing but pleasure continuity (no predictability), one can and has to vary, that is substitute one pleasure with another, as long as it is innocuous &lt;ins class=&quot;diffchange diffchange-inline&quot;&gt;and reachable&lt;/ins&gt;; otherwise they risk becoming border-less, i.e. whether stressful or vain, ''kene'' ', whether for internal (freedom, habits) or external (causes, competition/consumerism) factors rough confusion:&amp;#160; cithara hardly helps ears aching by contained cerumen [Hor. ''Ep.'' I.2.51]; only what is limited within its ambit is calculable&lt;ins class=&quot;diffchange diffchange-inline&quot;&gt;. Since it may change from natural into unnatural (without object) condition, it appears clearly as varying (''pokilma''), in movement (''kynêsis''), border-less (without object/void)&lt;/ins&gt;. Only in &lt;ins class=&quot;diffchange diffchange-inline&quot;&gt;opposite &lt;/ins&gt;case choice turns into an effective cognitive therapy (shared by intellectualist ethics of Skeptics and Epictetus) as is that of Principal Doctrines.&amp;#160; '''''(3)''''' &amp;lt;blockquote&amp;gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;“pursued with an intense effort, are also due to baseless opinion” [P.D. 30; as a consequence, too much vital values (gain, self-esteem, perfectionism, or, even worse, obsessive neuroticism) into an artist/hobbyist's work impoverish the joy of creativity; he acts without “more or less” [''kata to pleon ê elatton'', Epicurus ''Pherc'' 1056,&amp;#160; Arr. 34. 17; easygoingness] for goods being, after all, “limited in magnitude but also&amp;#160; easy to attain” [''Choices'', XIII]; “others are the result of habits [...] some originate in ourselves [...] others arise because of external factors [opponents fear turned in psychosomatic aches/wound], or because things, which became desirable by our lack of them, inflicted&amp;#160; (on us) [sometime like] a '''wound''' by the very thought of them.” [Phld.''Choices'', VI; and '''vulnus''' of DRN IV. 1049; or internal cause and possible projected opinion (hunger turned in greed, seldom vice versa); in that sense they are alike to Platonic 'mixed pleasures', that E. was remedying, bringing them back - by leveling out pleasures - to Platonic 'pure' pleasure].&amp;lt;/blockquote&amp;gt; &amp;#160;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;“pursued with an intense effort, are also due to baseless opinion” [P.D. 30; as a consequence, too much vital values (gain, self-esteem, perfectionism, or, even worse, obsessive neuroticism) into an artist/hobbyist's work impoverish the joy of creativity; he acts without “more or less” [''kata to pleon ê elatton'', Epicurus ''Pherc'' 1056,&amp;#160; Arr. 34. 17; easygoingness] for goods being, after all, “limited in magnitude but also&amp;#160; easy to attain” [''Choices'', XIII]; “others are the result of habits [...] some originate in ourselves [...] others arise because of external factors [opponents fear turned in psychosomatic aches/wound], or because things, which became desirable by our lack of them, inflicted&amp;#160; (on us) [sometime like] a '''wound''' by the very thought of them.” [Phld.''Choices'', VI; and '''vulnus''' of DRN IV. 1049; or internal cause and possible projected opinion (hunger turned in greed, seldom vice versa); in that sense they are alike to Platonic 'mixed pleasures', that E. was remedying, bringing them back - by leveling out pleasures - to Platonic 'pure' pleasure].&amp;lt;/blockquote&amp;gt; &amp;#160;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;One clear instance of&amp;#160; (potentially non natural) 'variable' kinetic desires is&amp;#160; wealth : &amp;quot;riches ... and other things which we [the Stoics, but chronologically Epicureanism precedes Stoicism, r.'s n.] call indifferent [but only Epicureans can consistently call them variables (in motion) because they admit chance, out of finalism], are neither good nor bad&amp;quot; [Epicurus at Sen. ''De Matrimonio'', fragments]. Without naming&amp;#160; Epicurus [&amp;quot;do you believe these thoughts to be only Epicurus', and not in the public domain?&amp;quot;; Sen. ''Epist.'' 8, 8] he expounds Epicurean ''On Wealth'': &amp;quot;The sage [..] doesn't long for riches, but '''accepts them''' [...] and d o e s n't&amp;#160;  a v o i d them [''De vita beata'', 21, 4 e 26; as “not bearing wealth is sign of weak soul” [''Epist.''&amp;#160; 5, 6], that is : &amp;quot;they have to be up to us, not we up to them&amp;quot; [''Ep.'' 98, 2]. Riches, residence have to be of service of us (to pejorative changes and present comforts),&amp;#160; not the other way around, becoming fetishes and emblems of superiority of rank; it may happen that such a natural desire becomes unnatural, so &amp;quot;Many men when they have acquired riches have not found the escape from their ills but have only exchanged them for greater ills&amp;quot; [V.S. 72; see Horace's Volteius Mena, ''Epist.'' I. 7. 95 ff.].&amp;lt;br&amp;gt; &amp;#160;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;One clear instance of&amp;#160; (potentially non natural) 'variable' kinetic desires is&amp;#160; wealth : &amp;quot;riches ... and other things which we [the Stoics, but chronologically Epicureanism precedes Stoicism, r.'s n.] call indifferent [but only Epicureans can consistently call them variables (in motion) because they admit chance, out of finalism], are neither good nor bad&amp;quot; [Epicurus at Sen. ''De Matrimonio'', fragments]. Without naming&amp;#160; Epicurus [&amp;quot;do you believe these thoughts to be only Epicurus', and not in the public domain?&amp;quot;; Sen. ''Epist.'' 8, 8] he expounds Epicurean ''On Wealth'': &amp;quot;The sage [..] doesn't long for riches, but '''accepts them''' [...] and d o e s n't&amp;#160;  a v o i d them [''De vita beata'', 21, 4 e 26; as “not bearing wealth is sign of weak soul” [''Epist.''&amp;#160; 5, 6], that is : &amp;quot;they have to be up to us, not we up to them&amp;quot; [''Ep.'' 98, 2]. Riches, residence have to be of service of us (to pejorative changes and present comforts),&amp;#160; not the other way around, becoming fetishes and emblems of superiority of rank; it may happen that such a natural desire becomes unnatural, so &amp;quot;Many men when they have acquired riches have not found the escape from their ills but have only exchanged them for greater ills&amp;quot; [V.S. 72; see Horace's Volteius Mena, ''Epist.'' I. 7. 95 ff.].&amp;lt;br&amp;gt; &amp;#160;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;</summary>
		<author><name>Giampaolo zennaro</name></author>	</entry>

