				&lt;td colspan='2' style=&quot;background-color: white; color:black; text-align: center;&quot;&gt;← Older revision&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td colspan='2' style=&quot;background-color: white; color:black; text-align: center;&quot;&gt;Revision as of 09:56, 28 January 2015&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td colspan=&quot;2&quot; class=&quot;diff-lineno&quot;&gt;Line 7:&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td colspan=&quot;2&quot; class=&quot;diff-lineno&quot;&gt;Line 7:&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;Epicurus had challenged certain axioms of Euclid, Zeno's of Elea paradox of Achilles and the tortoise,&amp;#160; binary logic of Stoics as negating the free practicability of life.&amp;#160; Incontrovertible mathematical logic and calculation would have been a sign of inflexible necessity of the world. He and then his followers Polyaenus, Philonides of Laodicea , Demetrius the Lacon, Zeno of Sidon expanded these courses, and raised the analogical calculation of 'more or less', of multiple results, of prudential ''epilogismos''.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;Epicurus had challenged certain axioms of Euclid, Zeno's of Elea paradox of Achilles and the tortoise,&amp;#160; binary logic of Stoics as negating the free practicability of life.&amp;#160; Incontrovertible mathematical logic and calculation would have been a sign of inflexible necessity of the world. He and then his followers Polyaenus, Philonides of Laodicea , Demetrius the Lacon, Zeno of Sidon expanded these courses, and raised the analogical calculation of 'more or less', of multiple results, of prudential ''epilogismos''.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;−&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;color:black; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #ffe49c; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;Through Zeno's ''Against the reply of Craterus to his On Geometrical Proofs'' (PHer 1533; now under digital endoscopy of Kleve &amp;amp; Dal Mastro) and Proclus, ''Comm. on Euclid'' 199 ff. (partisan)&amp;#160; some conjectural reconstructions of the issue he took against Euclid would be possible. &amp;lt;br&amp;gt;A real triangle, made of not elastic points, must have only one indivisible point/minimum on vertex of its angles. A triangle side is a line with two angles. But the other sides&amp;#160; [without one or two angles] “are both smaller&amp;quot;&amp;#160; (therefore “equilateral triangle cannot be built”, Proclus, 214), or each vertex point should be divisible by two, what is against definition of indivisible points/minima (''Taytê tê analogia nomisteon kai to en '''elachiston''' kechrêsthai''; ''Ep. Hrdt'' 58). For instance an equilateral triangle with side three empirical points (to day verified as 'quanta') has a perimeter of six points, not nine. If divided in three each side is one plus two half point, that cannot be. If a triangle is divided in half, one half is a little bit larger.&amp;#160; Are certain points of Euclid anytime further divisible, while the others aren't? In that case all points are irrational/adaptable i.e. analogical (like slide rule), and it should&amp;#160; be said that limits and integrals approach in circumstantial variable speed…&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;+&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;color:black; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #a3d3ff; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;Through Zeno's ''Against the reply of Craterus to his On Geometrical Proofs'' (PHer 1533; now under digital endoscopy of Kleve &amp;amp; Dal Mastro) and Proclus, ''Comm. on Euclid'' 199 ff. (partisan)&amp;#160; some conjectural reconstructions of the issue he took against Euclid would be possible. &amp;lt;br&amp;gt;A real triangle, made of not elastic points, must have only one indivisible point/minimum &lt;ins class=&quot;diffchange diffchange-inline&quot;&gt;(''elachiston'') &lt;/ins&gt;on vertex of its angles. A triangle side is a line with two angles. But the other sides&amp;#160; [without one or two angles] “are both smaller&amp;quot;&amp;#160; (therefore “equilateral triangle cannot be built”, Proclus, 214), or each vertex point should be divisible by two, what is against definition of indivisible points/minima (''Taytê tê analogia nomisteon kai to en '''elachiston''' kechrêsthai''; ''Ep. Hrdt'' 58). For instance an equilateral triangle with side three empirical points (to day verified as 'quanta') has a perimeter of six points, not nine. If divided in three each side is one plus two half point, that cannot be. If a triangle is divided in half, one half is a little bit larger.&amp;#160; Are certain points of Euclid anytime further divisible, while the others aren't? In that case all points are irrational/adaptable i.e. analogical (like slide rule), and it should&amp;#160; be said that limits and integrals approach in circumstantial variable speed…&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;Hypotenuse turned out irrational: that hit Pythagoras and Plato hard.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;Hypotenuse turned out irrational: that hit Pythagoras and Plato hard.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;The real circle area, whose irrationality is obvious (3.14...), is incalculable for the same reason: vertexes of infinite circumscribing/inscribed multi-polygons - formed by basic (after Plato) triangles - cannot have real diameters that go across the center, because they cannot be split (minimum and point concept) (Proclus, 216).&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;The real circle area, whose irrationality is obvious (3.14...), is incalculable for the same reason: vertexes of infinite circumscribing/inscribed multi-polygons - formed by basic (after Plato) triangles - cannot have real diameters that go across the center, because they cannot be split (minimum and point concept) (Proclus, 216).&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;</summary>
		<author><name>Giampaolo zennaro</name></author>	</entry>

