				&lt;tr style='vertical-align: top;'&gt;
				&lt;td colspan='2' style=&quot;background-color: white; color:black; text-align: center;&quot;&gt;← Older revision&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td colspan='2' style=&quot;background-color: white; color:black; text-align: center;&quot;&gt;Revision as of 09:51, 27 January 2015&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td colspan=&quot;2&quot; class=&quot;diff-lineno&quot;&gt;Line 1:&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td colspan=&quot;2&quot; class=&quot;diff-lineno&quot;&gt;Line 1:&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;Epicurus' Philosophy is more deductive (with critical awareness) than generally has been thought, modelling itself, after Euclid, by intuitive postulates ''ai dôdeca stocheiôsis'' [U56]&amp;#160; the '''Twelve Elementary Propositions'''. 1 Matter is uncreatable, 2 Matter is indistructible, 3 The universe consists of solid bodies and void , 4 Solid bodies are either compounds or simple, 5 The multitude of atoms is infinite, 6 The void is infinite in extent, 7 The atoms are always in motion, 8 The speed of atomic motion is uniform, 9 Motion is linear in space, vibratory in compounds, 10 Atoms are capable of swerving slightly at any point in space or time, 11 Atoms are characterized by three qualities, weight, shape and size,&amp;#160; 12 The number of the different shapes is not infinite, merely innumerable.&amp;#160; All former propositions are primary knowledge, secondary is derivative (from DRN books I-II, and De Witt); only ''antimartyrêsis''/falsifiability and non-counter-claim (''ouk antimartyrêsis'') are inductive. He realizes that postulates and derivative propositions ('words&amp;#160; explanation' [''On Nature XXV'']) cannot be debatable (we say analytic propositions are tautological), but “ If you arbitrarily reject [...] every intuitive faculty of mind, you will impute trouble to all other sensory experiences, thereby rejecting every criterion” [P.D. 24]. So, for our life completeness, living with pleasure (sensory experience), total demonstrability is not necessary, as Demetrius the Laconian says: &amp;quot; In the work entitled ''Kyriai Doxai'', Epicurus says that the [end is pleasure] [teaching that] it [needs] no demonstration&amp;quot; [''Textual Aporias'' fr. 52, Pherc 1012, Delattre]. His intuitive deductive ''physiologia'' has been almost strengthened by our physics. It is a result of scientific epistemology that has excluded any authoritarian dogmatism but fear of positive law (P.D. 34, “injustice is not an evil in and by itself”), and an elementary ''prolêpsis'' of justice, “not to inflict nor allow harm” and “to benefit human interactions” (usefulness), that does not include distributive justice, nor a standard of punishment that are relative ''ypolêpseis'', that is 'agreements'. He needed a philosophy of&amp;#160; ''ataraxia'', free from vain hopes, fear of Gods and guilty feelings and a world outlook set out by limits toward ''isonomia'', balance of opposites and ''katastematik'' stable desires.&amp;lt;br&amp;gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;Epicurus' Philosophy is more deductive (with critical awareness) than generally has been thought, modelling itself, after Euclid, by intuitive postulates ''ai dôdeca stocheiôsis'' [U56]&amp;#160; the '''Twelve Elementary Propositions'''. 1 Matter is uncreatable, 2 Matter is indistructible, 3 The universe consists of solid bodies and void , 4 Solid bodies are either compounds or simple, 5 The multitude of atoms is infinite, 6 The void is infinite in extent, 7 The atoms are always in motion, 8 The speed of atomic motion is uniform, 9 Motion is linear in space, vibratory in compounds, 10 Atoms are capable of swerving slightly at any point in space or time, 11 Atoms are characterized by three qualities, weight, shape and size,&amp;#160; 12 The number of the different shapes is not infinite, merely innumerable.&amp;#160; All former propositions are primary knowledge, secondary is derivative (from DRN books I-II, and De Witt); only ''antimartyrêsis''/falsifiability and non-counter-claim (''ouk antimartyrêsis'') are inductive. He realizes that postulates and derivative propositions ('words&amp;#160; explanation' [''On Nature XXV'']) cannot be debatable (we say analytic propositions are tautological), but “ If you arbitrarily reject [...] every intuitive faculty of mind, you will impute trouble to all other sensory experiences, thereby rejecting every criterion” [P.D. 24]. So, for our life completeness, living with pleasure (sensory experience), total demonstrability is not necessary, as Demetrius the Laconian says: &amp;quot; In the work entitled ''Kyriai Doxai'', Epicurus says that the [end is pleasure] [teaching that] it [needs] no demonstration&amp;quot; [''Textual Aporias'' fr. 52, Pherc 1012, Delattre]. His intuitive deductive ''physiologia'' has been almost strengthened by our physics. It is a result of scientific epistemology that has excluded any authoritarian dogmatism but fear of positive law (P.D. 34, “injustice is not an evil in and by itself”), and an elementary ''prolêpsis'' of justice, “not to inflict nor allow harm” and “to benefit human interactions” (usefulness), that does not include distributive justice, nor a standard of punishment that are relative ''ypolêpseis'', that is 'agreements'. He needed a philosophy of&amp;#160; ''ataraxia'', free from vain hopes, fear of Gods and guilty feelings and a world outlook set out by limits toward ''isonomia'', balance of opposites and ''katastematik'' stable desires.&amp;lt;br&amp;gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;As Stoics reasoned necessity principle with a logical proposition - that says nothing about actual weather conditions - ('tomorrow it'll raining or not raining': it's necessary and ''tertium non datur''),&amp;#160; Epicurus likely and logically deduced that sometime necessity is not there, since 'all is necessary' is logically self confuting. Human trial-and-error synaptic links, alias soul's atoms course, are not programmed from somebody and knowledge can't define its future beliefs and our ensuing innovatory deeds. &amp;#160;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;As Stoics reasoned necessity principle with a logical proposition - that says nothing about actual weather conditions - ('tomorrow it'll raining or not raining': it's necessary and ''tertium non datur''),&amp;#160; Epicurus likely and logically deduced that sometime necessity is not there, since 'all is necessary' is logically self confuting. Human trial-and-error synaptic links, alias soul's atoms course, are not programmed from somebody and knowledge can't define its future beliefs and our ensuing innovatory deeds. &amp;#160;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;−&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;color:black; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #ffe49c; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;Total necessity would imply that '''all''' atoms have a '''linear, one-way, external causality''' Epicurus graphically designed&amp;#160; as linear&amp;#160; and parallel movement of atoms; non necessity, as a swerve, implying a crossroad/node with affirmation or negation. Since the thought has '''negation''' capability ''antimartyrêsis'', - i.e. no one-way straight motion, so there must be there some soul atoms alternative ways/crossroads &lt;del class=&quot;diffchange diffchange-inline&quot;&gt; &lt;/del&gt;without necessity, that is with steering (''paregklisis''/swerve) as may be watched in capillary vessels.&amp;lt;br&amp;gt; &amp;#160;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;+&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;color:black; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #a3d3ff; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;Total necessity would imply that '''all''' atoms have a '''linear, one-way, external causality''' Epicurus graphically designed&amp;#160; as linear&amp;#160; and parallel movement of atoms; non necessity, as a swerve, implying a crossroad/node with affirmation or negation&lt;ins class=&quot;diffchange diffchange-inline&quot;&gt;; multiple explanation implies a 'tree' causality, a conglomerate 'vibration' is a circuit causality or retro-action loop&lt;/ins&gt;. Since the thought &lt;ins class=&quot;diffchange diffchange-inline&quot;&gt;(immediate and complex atoms movement) &lt;/ins&gt;has '''negation''' capability ''antimartyrêsis'', - i.e. no one-way straight motion, so there must be there some soul atoms alternative ways/crossroads &lt;ins class=&quot;diffchange diffchange-inline&quot;&gt;(and a 'tree' choice) &lt;/ins&gt;without necessity, that is with steering (''paregklisis''/swerve) as may be watched in capillary vessels.&amp;lt;br&amp;gt; &amp;#160;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;−&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;color:black; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #ffe49c; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;It was no far-fletched logicism about Physics: today Networks Theory – starting from Poincaré and &lt;del class=&quot;diffchange diffchange-inline&quot;&gt;Eulero &lt;/del&gt;- considers non linear causality;&amp;#160; the very artificial thought/cybernetic designs&amp;#160; a web of retro-actions/feedbacks, which say no to deterministic second principle of thermodynamics (' '''negative'''- entropy', order trend, creativity).&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;+&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;color:black; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #a3d3ff; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;It was no far-fletched logicism about Physics: today Networks Theory – starting from Poincaré and &lt;ins class=&quot;diffchange diffchange-inline&quot;&gt;Euler &lt;/ins&gt;- considers non linear causality;&amp;#160; the very artificial thought/cybernetic designs&amp;#160; a web of retro-actions/feedbacks, which say no to deterministic second principle of thermodynamics (' '''negative'''- entropy', order trend, creativity).&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;−&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;color:black; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #ffe49c; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;A necessity theorist cannot demonstrate his opposer is wrong, since he couldn't freely be in agreement with the opposite point of view that his personal necessity&amp;#160; &lt;del class=&quot;diffchange diffchange-inline&quot;&gt;unfaily &lt;/del&gt;don't allow, and bestows no alternative (negation) to his way of thinking: “He who says that all things happen by necessity can hardly find fault with the one who denies that all happens by necessity; for on his own theory this very argument is voiced by necessity” [V.S. 40], not by independent truthfulness... We are entitled to believe our brain is able to develop its 'applications' negating some external necessities by flight or shelters.&amp;lt;br&amp;gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;+&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;color:black; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #a3d3ff; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;A necessity theorist cannot demonstrate his opposer is wrong, since he couldn't freely be in agreement with the opposite point of view that his personal necessity&amp;#160; &lt;ins class=&quot;diffchange diffchange-inline&quot;&gt;unfairly &lt;/ins&gt;don't allow, and bestows no alternative (negation) to his way of thinking &lt;ins class=&quot;diffchange diffchange-inline&quot;&gt;(nor the improvement of kinetic desires)&lt;/ins&gt;: “He who says that all things happen by necessity can hardly find fault with the one who denies that all happens by necessity; for on his own theory this very argument is voiced by necessity” [V.S. 40], not by independent truthfulness... We are entitled to believe our brain is able to develop its 'applications' negating some external necessities by flight or shelters.&amp;lt;br&amp;gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;Everything happens by necessity being self-confuting and '''there is always negation''' being self-confuting too (since one is affirming it) imply that&amp;#160; ''' 'Not everything' ''' happens by necessity - as a contrary- may be true under situations, and that sometime is there necessity,&amp;#160; sometime necessity is not, since one can choose after his own desires [like says D.L. 134]. Non necessity, as a swerve, implies a crossroad/node (instead of vessels ... today synapses)&amp;#160; with affirmation or negation; that a negation is there into one's mind one is sure, since denying it is the evidence of its existence, and that's enough for one's pleasure attainableness and freedom, the negation of some external causality. &amp;quot;Concentrated together [atoms], [...] are by nature capable of producing such things and starting such a process&amp;quot; [ ''On Nature'' Book XXV PHerc. 697, [34. 4] ARR.].&amp;#160; (“mind's primitive constitution” ”with its own causality” [ ''Perì Physeos'' VIII Pap. 1056/697/1191.7. Arrighetti]. Since the age of two, the human being can always say no in every situation, hopefully with thoughtfulness.&amp;lt;br&amp;gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;Everything happens by necessity being self-confuting and '''there is always negation''' being self-confuting too (since one is affirming it) imply that&amp;#160; ''' 'Not everything' ''' happens by necessity - as a contrary- may be true under situations, and that sometime is there necessity,&amp;#160; sometime necessity is not, since one can choose after his own desires [like says D.L. 134]. Non necessity, as a swerve, implies a crossroad/node (instead of vessels ... today synapses)&amp;#160; with affirmation or negation; that a negation is there into one's mind one is sure, since denying it is the evidence of its existence, and that's enough for one's pleasure attainableness and freedom, the negation of some external causality. &amp;quot;Concentrated together [atoms], [...] are by nature capable of producing such things and starting such a process&amp;quot; [ ''On Nature'' Book XXV PHerc. 697, [34. 4] ARR.].&amp;#160; (“mind's primitive constitution” ”with its own causality” [ ''Perì Physeos'' VIII Pap. 1056/697/1191.7. Arrighetti]. Since the age of two, the human being can always say no in every situation, hopefully with thoughtfulness.&amp;lt;br&amp;gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;From the same reasoning, as one cannot determine natural desires, Epicurus inferred that negation - as a constituent element of the world - implies also limitation of freedom (''elachiston''), and ''isonomia'' (balancing of opposites) can be theorized: &amp;#160;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td class='diff-marker'&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;background-color: #f9f9f9; color: #333333; font-size: 88%; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px 1px 1px 4px; border-radius: 0.33em; border-color: #e6e6e6; vertical-align: top; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;From the same reasoning, as one cannot determine natural desires, Epicurus inferred that negation - as a constituent element of the world - implies also limitation of freedom (''elachiston''), and ''isonomia'' (balancing of opposites) can be theorized: &amp;#160;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
